Locality: Cornell Research Ponds Unit I (restricted access)

Observation Details: Pair seen feeding fledgling ~50 yards north of the parking lot. Magnolia Warblers are found each breeding season around Beacon Heights, but to my knowledge, this is the first instance of nesting being confirmed here. Both adult birds were easily detectable by their distinct call note (recording below). The female was particularly vocal as she actively gathered food in the vicinity of the fledgling, always giving the largest insects to the fledgling and keeping the smaller ones for herself. The male was mostly silent, and never fed the fledgling while I was there. Interestingly, I watched the female chase the male away from the fledgling four times while I was there, and sometimes he would fly across the road and not return to the female for extended periods of time.
